The @Soviet Union in American school textbooks
publ. for the American Association of Public Opinion Research

Presentation of the Soviet Union in American school textbooks is in general sketchy and poorly balanced, and is subject to bias and factual inaccuracies in some cases. This situation is not peculiar to presentation of the Soviet Union, however, but applies to treatment of almost all foreign nations. For example, textbook material regarding Canada is subject to limitations almost equally serious. It is suggested that an important step on the road to international understanding would be to present other nations more fully and accurately to the coming generation. This article may be considered a companion piece to Soviet Version of American History, by George S. Counts, which appeared in the Fall, 1946, issue of this journal. The author is Dual Professor of Social Science and Education at Syracuse University, and Director of the American Council on Education's Study of the Soviet Union in Social Studies Teaching Materials.
